The Church of Ireland is divided into 12 dioceses, each with its own bishop and cathedral. These dioceses are as follows: 

1. Armagh Diocese, which encompasses the majority of County Armagh and parts of Counties Tyrone and Londonderry, with its cathedral in Armagh City; 

2. Clogher Diocese, which covers the majority of County Tyrone and parts of Counties Fermanagh and Monaghan, with its cathedral in Clogher; 

3. Connor Diocese, which includes the majority of County Antrim and parts of Counties Down and Londonderry, with its cathedral in Belfast; 

4. Derry and Raphoe Diocese, which covers the majority of Counties Londonderry and Donegal, with its cathedral in Londonderry; 

5. Down and Dromore Diocese, which encompasses the majority of County Down and parts of County Armagh, with its cathedral in Downpatrick; 

6. Dublin and Glendalough Diocese, which covers the majority of County Dublin and parts of Counties Wicklow and Wexford, with its cathedral in Dublin; 

7. Cashel, Ferns and Ossory Diocese, which includes the majority of Counties Tipperary, Kilkenny, and Wexford, with its cathedral in Cashel; 

8. Cork, Cloyne and Ross Diocese, which covers the majority of County Cork, with its cathedral in Cork City; 

9. Limerick and Killaloe Diocese, which encompasses the majority of Counties Limerick and Clare, with its cathedral in Limerick City; 

10. Meath and Kildare Diocese, which covers the majority of Counties Meath and Kildare, with its cathedral in Trim; 

11. Tuam, Killala and Achonry Diocese, which includes the majority of Counties Galway and Mayo, with its cathedral in Tuam; 

12. Kilmore, Elphin and Ardagh Diocese, which covers the majority of Counties Cavan, Leitrim, and Longford, with its cathedral in Cavan.
